ly Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: occupational name for a steward or bailiff, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>schaffen</i> ‘to manage’. It is also found in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Denmark, Czechia, Slovakia, and Slovenia; see also 3 below.","South German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (<b>Schäffer</b>): variant of <b>Schäfer</b> (see   Schaefer  ). It is also found in Hungary, Denmark, Czechia, Slovakia, and Slovenia. Compare   Cheffer  ,   Schaeffer  ,   Shaeffer  ,   Shafer  ,   Shaffer  , and   Sheaffer  .","Germanized form of Hungarian <b>Sáfár</b>, Slovenian and Croatian <b>Šafar</b> or <b>Šafer</b>, Czech <b>Šafář</b> or <b>Šafer</b>, Slovak <b>Šafár</b>, cognates of 1 above (see   Safar  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Safar","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Fahim, Ammar, Mazin, Safar, Abdallah, Abdulrahman, Antoun, Fadel, Faisal, Farid, Fereydoun, Haitham.  French Gaston, Antoine.  Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian Ignac, Pavel, Zdenka.","Arabic and Jewish (from North Africa): occupational name from Arabic <i>ṣaffār</i> ‘coppersmith, worker in copper or brass’.","Arabic: from the personal name <i>Ṣafar</i>, from <i>ṣafar</i>, the name of the second month of the Islamic calendar. This is sometimes chosen as a personal name for children born in this month. Bearers of this surname are both Muslims and Christians."]},{"name":"Sheaffer","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Schäffer</b> (see   Schaffer   2)."]},{"name":"Schaeffer","meanings":["German (<b>Schäffer</b>):","see   Schaffer   2.","variant of <b>Schäfer</b> (see   Schaefer  )."]},{"name":"Shaeffer","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Schäffer</b> (see   Schaffer   2)."]},{"name":"Scheffer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of <b>Schäffer</b> (see   Schaffer   2). It is also found in Hungary."]},{"name":"Schaffner","meanings":["German: occupational name for a steward or bailiff, a variant 